<item>
  <title>Scheduling exports of your static site from WordPress</title>
  <link>http://172.17.0.3/2018/05/11/scheduling-exports-of-your-static-site-from-wordpress/</link>
  <pubDate>Fri, 11 May 2018 14:27:47 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>admin</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://172.17.0.3/?p=5</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[You can use the <a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/wp-crontrol/">WP Crontrol</a> plugin to schedule the export of your static site.

This feature is yet to be released into the official version of <a href="http://wordpress.org/plugins/static-html-output-plugin/">WP Static HTML Output Plugin</a>, but you can try it out by downloading the latest development version of the plugin from the <a href="http://github.com/leonstafford/wordpress-static-html-plugin">GitHub repository</a>.
<h2>Scheduling your WordPress site to be exported as a static HTML site</h2>
<ol>
 	<li>Install the <a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/wp-crontrol/">WP Crontrol</a> plugin.</li>
 	<li>Go to your Cron Schedules via Settings &gt; Cron Schedules
<a href="http://172.17.0.3/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/go_to_cron_schedules.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-11 size-full" src="http://172.17.0.3/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/go_to_cron_schedules.png" alt="" width="406" height="375" /></a></li>
 	<li>Add a new Cron Schedule, using WP Static HTML Output's custom hook, setting the following options:
<ol>
 	<li><strong> Internal name:</strong> <em>wp_static_html_output_server_side_export_hook</em></li>
 	<li><strong>Interval (seconds):</strong> ie <em>3600</em> to run your export every hour, <em>86400</em> for daily exports, etc</li>
 	<li><strong>Display name:</strong> This can be whatever you like. Something that makes sense to you is recommended, ie "<em>Static site export to S3 once a day</em>" <a style="font-size: 1rem;" href="http://172.17.0.3/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/wpcrontrol_add_scheduled_task.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-8" src="http://172.17.0.3/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/wpcrontrol_add_scheduled_task-1024x545.png" alt="" width="800" height="426" /></a></li>
</ol>
</li>
 	<li>Click on Add Cron Schedule to save your scheduled task. It should now appear in your list of tasks, as below: <a style="font-size: 1rem;" href="http://172.17.0.3/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/wp_crontrol_added_task.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-7" src="http://172.17.0.3/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/wp_crontrol_added_task-1024x490.png" alt="" width="800" height="383" /></a></li>
</ol>
&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>
